history.content:
I took it Spring 2018 alongside ee126, ee127, and a breadth.

The first project you are preforming exploits, such as buffer overflows. If you're not someone who is comfortable with debugging in C or looking at the layout of memory, then this project could take a little while. The second project is notorious for its many, many edge cases. You are essentially making a file storage system that has to obey various important security constraints. During my year we also had to design for efficiency. My partner and I spent quite a bit of time on this, and most people tend to. The last project dealt with the web and thanks to a TA for providing an awesome UI, this was perhaps the most enjoyable of the three. Probably the easiest too. There are also homework assignments, but they tend to be fairly straightforward. Overall I would say it is a medium workload class because I spent a lot of time just trying to figure out what was going on in the projects. Perhaps this won't be you and you'll get most of the concepts fairly easily.

You'll have a tough semester nonetheless, particularly with 189, but if you stay on top of your work, you should be good to go!

children.subject: It also depends on how good you are with that material in general. I apparently really suck at it, and it took me more time than I had (both in general and in the time given for the projects). If you’re comfortable with it, it can be fairly quick. If you’re like me and have zero talent at it, it will be a very long semester.
